problem:
Points $A,$ $B,$ and $C$ are placed on a circle centered at $O$ as in the following diagram: [asy]
pair pA, pB, pC, pO;
pO = (0, 0);
pA = pO + dir(-40);
pB = pO + dir(32);
pC = pO + dir(176);
draw(pA--pO--pB--pC--pA);
label("$O$", pO, 2 * E);
label("$A$", pA, SE);
label("$B$", pB, NE);
label("$C$", pC, W);
draw(circle(pO, 1));
[/asy] If $AC = BC$ and $\angle OAC = 18^\circ,$ then how many degrees are in $\angle AOB$?

solution:
First, let us draw $CO$: [asy]
pair pA, pB, pC, pO;
pO = (0, 0);
pA = pO + dir(-40);
pB = pO + dir(32);
pC = pO + dir(176);
draw(pA--pO--pB--pC--pA);
draw(pO--pC);
label("$O$", pO, 2 * E);
label("$A$", pA, SE);
label("$B$", pB, NE);
label("$C$", pC, W);
draw(circle(pO, 1));
[/asy] Since $AO = CO,$ we have that $\triangle AOC$ is isosceles, and so $\angle CAO = \angle ACO = 18^\circ.$ We are given that $AC = BC,$ we can see that $\triangle BOC \cong \triangle AOC,$  so $\angle BCO = 18^\circ.$ Now, $\angle ACB = \angle OAC + \angle BCO = 36^\circ,$ and as $\angle ACB$ is an inscribed angle, we have $\angle AOB = 2 \cdot \angle ACB = \boxed{72^\circ}.$

